JavaScript Map Methods:

1) The new Map() Method:
    - You can create a map by passing an array to the new Map() constructor:
            // Create a 
            const fruits = new Map();
                or,
            const fruits = new Map([
                ["apples", 500],
                ["bananas", 300],
                ["oranges", 200]
            ]);


2) Map.get():
    - You get the value of a key in a map with the get() method
        fruits.get("apples");   // 500
    
3) Map.set(): to add new element and change the existing element.
    - You can add elements to a map with the set() method:
        // Create a Map
        const fruits = new Map();

        // Set Map Values
        fruits.set("apples", 500);
        fruits.set("bananas", 300);
        fruits.set("oranges", 200);
    
    - The set() method can also be used to change existing map values:
        // change the existing element
        fruits.set("apples", 500);

4) Map.size:
    - The size property returns the number of elements in a map:
        const fruits = new Map([
            ["apples", 500],
            ["bananas", 300],
            ["oranges", 200]
        ]);

        fruits.size;    // 3


5) Map.delete():
    - The delete() method removes a map element:
        const fruits = new Map([
            ["apples", 500],
            ["bananas", 300],
            ["oranges", 200]
        ]);

        fruits.delete("apples");   


6) Map.clear():
    - The clear() method removes all the elements from a map:
        const fruits = new Map([
            ["apples", 500],
            ["bananas", 300],
            ["oranges", 200]
        ]);

        fruits.clear();   


7) Map.has():
    - The has() method returns true if a key exists in a map:
        fruits.has("apples");   // true

        fruits.delete("apples");
        fruits.has("apples");   // false


8) Map.forEach():
    - The forEach() method invokes a callback for each key/value pair in a map:
        // List all entries
        let text = "";
        fruits.forEach (function(value, key) {
            text += key + ' = ' + value;
        })


9) Map.entries():
    - The entries() method returns an iterator object with the [key,values] in a map:
        // List all entries
        let text = "";
        for (const x of fruits.entries()) {
            text += x;
        }
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;

        o/p:    apples,500
                bananas,300
                oranges,200


10) Map.keys():
    - The keys() method returns an iterator object with the keys in a map:
        // List all keys
        let text = "";
        for (const x of fruits.keys()) {
            text += x + "<br>";
        }

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;

        o/p:    apples
                bananas
                oranges


11) Map.values():
    - The values() method returns an iterator object with the values in a map:
        // Create a Map
        const fruits = new Map([
            ["apples", 500],
            ["bananas", 300],
            ["oranges", 200]
        ]);

        let text = "";
        for (const x of fruits.values()) {
            text += x + "<br>";
        }

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;

        o/p:    500
                300
                200
        
    - You can use the values() method to sum the values in a map:
        let total = 0;
        for (const x of fruits.values()) {
            total += x;
        }

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = total;  //1000


💡) Objects as Keys:
    - Being able to use objects as keys is an important Map feature.
        // Create Objects
        const apples = {name: 'Apples'};
        const bananas = {name: 'Bananas'};
        const oranges = {name: 'Oranges'};

        // Create a Map
        const fruits = new Map();

        // Add new Elements to the Map
        fruits.set(apples, 500);
        fruits.set(bananas, 300);
        fruits.set(oranges, 200);

        fruits.get("apples");  // ❌ Returns undefined
        fruits.get(apples);   // ✅ 500


12) JavaScript Map.groupBy()
    - ES2024 added the Map.groupBy() method to JavaScript.
    - The Map.groupBy() method groups elements of an object according to string values returned from
        a callback function.
    - 💡The Map.groupBy() method does not change the original object.

        // Create an Array
        const fruits = [
            {name:"apples", quantity:300},
            {name:"bananas", quantity:500},
            {name:"oranges", quantity:200},
            {name:"kiwi", quantity:150}
        ];

        // callback function to group by quantity
        function callback({quantity}) {
            return quantity > 300 ? "high" : "low";
        }

        // group the array elements using Map.groupBy()
        const grouped = Map.groupBy(fruits, callback);

        // display the result
        let text = "";
        for(let x of grouped.get("low")) {
            text += x.name + " (" + x.quantity + ")<br>";
        }
        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = "Grouped by quantity(low): <br> " + text;
        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML = "Original array: <br>" + JSON.stringify(fruits);

        o/p:    Grouped by quantity(low):
                apples (300)
                oranges (200)
                kiwi (150)


#) Object.groupBy() vs Map.groupBy():
    👉 The difference between Object.groupBy() and Map.groupBy() is:
    👉 Object.groupBy() groups elements into a JavaScript object.
    👉 Map.groupBy() groups elements into a Map object.